=== Rail passenger efficiency versus other modes ===
[[Image:Coast Starlight San Jose 01.jpg|thumb|Bi-level [[Superliner (railcar)|Superliner]] cars, used on long-distance routes, except in the Northeast because of height issues.]]
[[Image:Amtrak California.JPG|thumb|Standard locomotive used for ''Capitol Corridor'' and ''San Joaquin'' service]]
[[Image:Surfliner.jpg|thumb|Standard ''Pacific Surfliner'' trainset]]

Per passenger mile, Amtrak is 30<U+2013>40&nbsp;percent more energy-efficient than commercial airlines and automobiles overall,<ref name="bts-energy">Except where noted, figures are from 2006. {{cite web | title=Table 4-20: Energy Intensity of Passenger Modes | work=Bureau of Transportation Statistics | accessdate=2006-11-17 | url=http://www.bts.gov/publications/national_transportation_statistics/html/table_04_20.html}}</ref> though the exact figures for particular routes depend on load factor along with other variables.  The electrified trains in the Northeast Corridor are considerably more efficient than Amtrak's diesels and can feed energy captured from [[Regenerative brake#The motor as a brake|regenerative braking]] back to the electrical grid.  Passenger rail is also competitive with other modes in terms of safety per mile.

